Five Truths about Terrorism
SÃO PAULO – American policy is held hostage by terrorism.
In December 2015, polls indicated that one in six Americans, or about 16% of the population, now placed terrorism at the top of the country's problems – an increase of 3% in a month.
For ten years, no so many Americans have ever been so concerned about terrorism, although their numbers are still far below the 46% recorded immediately after the September 11, 2001 attacks.
The consequences of this shift in public opinion were most evident during the Republican primary for the presidential election.
Donald Trump's candidacy, whose anti-Muslim rhetoric is particularly fiery (if not incendiary), definitely benefited from it.
Some politicians allow themselves to refer to the battle against terrorism as the « Third World War.»
Terrorism is a problem for the United States, as shown by the San Bernardino attack in California last December.
But the presidential candidates, just like some media, who follow the old adage « if it bleeds, it leads », have exaggerated the proportions.
To place terrorism in its true perspective, Americans should – like others – keep the following considerations in mind:
Terrorism is a kind of theater.
Terrorists care more about holding attention and grabbing political headlines than the number, in itself, of their victims.
The Islamic State (IS) takes great care with its staging.
The brutal decapitations broadcasted on social media are intended to destabilize and scandalize – and therefore to monopolize attention.
Exaggerating their consequences and making big headlines with every terrorist act is playing into the terrorists' game.
Terrorism is not the most serious threat facing populations in developed countries.
Terrorism kills far less than road accidents or smoking.
From this perspective, terrorism is not even a real threat – neither major nor minor.
You are more likely to be struck by lightning than to be killed by a terrorist.
The probability that an American citizen is killed by a terrorist, according to experts, is one in 3.5 million.
Americans are more likely to die in their bathtub (a probability of 1 in 950,000), from a domestic appliance accident (1 in 1.5 million), from a deer or moose crossing the road (1 in 2 million), or in a commercial plane crash (1 in 2.9 million).
Six thousand Americans die every year while driving while texting or conversing on their cell phone.
This is hundreds of times the number of those who die from terrorism.
Radical Islamic terrorism kills fewer Americans than attacks carried out by disgruntled employees or mass shootings on campuses or in schools.
Terrorism is not the Third World War.
The global terrorism is not new.
It often takes a generation to extinguish a terrorist surge.
At the beginning of the 20th century, the anarchist movement killed a number of state leaders in the name of utopian ideals.
During the 1960s and 1970s, the Red Brigades and the Red Army Faction, stemming from the "autonomous" left, diverted airplanes outside national borders and kidnapped or killed business leaders or political figures (but also ordinary citizens).
Today's extremist jihadists are an old political phenomenon draped in religious attire.
Many of their leaders are not fundamentalists in the traditional sense, but people whose identity has been destroyed by globalization, seeking meaning in the imaginary and pure community of an Islamic caliphate.
It will take time and effort to defeat them, but the restrictive nature of ISIS limits its appeal.
Its sectarian attacks already prevent it from addressing all Muslims, let alone Hindus, Christians, or other believers.
ISIS will eventually be defeated, just as previous transnational terrorist groups have been.
Terrorism is like judo.
The weaker of the two adversaries uses the strength of the stronger to defeat him.
No terrorist organization has the power of a state, and few terrorist movements have managed to overthrow one.
But if they succeed in shocking and provoking enough citizens of a state to push them into futile actions, they may hope to gain the upper hand.
In 2001, Al-Qaida managed to draw the Americans into Afghanistan.
ISIS was born in the ruins of the U.S.-led invasion of Iraq, which followed the intervention in Afghanistan.
To defeat terrorism, one needs smart power.
Smart power is the ability to combine the coercive power (hard power) of the military and police with the influence power (soft power) of seduction and persuasion.
Influence power is also necessary if we want to immunize those on the periphery and those who the irreconcilables seek to recruit.
That is why the attention given to the narrative of events and how the actions of the United States are commented on social networks is as important and necessary as precision air strikes.
The rhetoric of confrontation, which points fingers at Muslims and alienates the good will that would allow us to obtain crucial information, puts us all in danger.
The reason why the anti-Islam stance of some current presidential candidates is so counterproductive.
The terrorist issue is serious, and it deserves to be placed among the priorities of our intelligence and police services, our armed forces, and our diplomacy.
It constitutes an important factor in our foreign policy.
And it is essential to keep weapons of mass destruction out of terrorists' reach.
But we must not fall into the trap set by terrorists.
Let us not fill the theatre where actions carried out by brutes and thugs take place.
If we hand over the great stage of our public speech to them, we will weaken the quality of our civic life and betray our priorities.
Our strength would then be used against us.
